00:05:19,820 --> 00:05:23,180
 How do you know your faith is genuine?

134
00:05:23,180 --> 00:05:26,300
 And even if I was to ask this more directly,

135
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:29,460
 does the faith you profess match up

136
00:05:29,460 --> 00:05:31,680
 with the way we live our life?

137
00:05:31,680 --> 00:05:36,060
 Do we have the kind of faith that God is looking for?

138
00:05:36,060 --> 00:05:38,560
 And if so, what are some of the hallmarks

139
00:05:38,560 --> 00:05:42,040
 that genuine faith in Jesus looks like?

140
00:05:42,040 --> 00:05:44,580
 As we walk through the book of James,

141
00:05:44,580 --> 00:05:46,960
 you're gonna figure out this is the kind of faith

142
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:49,580
 that doesn't get tossed and turned around

143
00:05:49,580 --> 00:05:51,740
 with the trials of life.

144
00:05:51,740 --> 00:05:54,620
 It's a faith that's completely counter-cultural

145
00:05:54,620 --> 00:05:57,100
 to the ways of this world.

146
00:05:57,100 --> 00:06:01,900
 It's a kind of faith that is accompanied with action.

147
00:06:01,900 --> 00:06:03,980
 So like I said, James chapter two,

148
00:06:03,980 --> 00:06:06,620
 we're gonna open it up, this is what it says.

149
00:06:06,620 --> 00:06:08,940
 My brothers and sisters,

150
00:06:08,940 --> 00:06:12,260
 believers in our glorious Lord Jesus Christ

151
00:06:12,260 --> 00:06:15,780
 must not show favoritism.

152
00:06:15,780 --> 00:06:17,480
 Suppose a man comes into your meeting

153
00:06:17,480 --> 00:06:19,340
 wearing a gold ring and fine clothes,

154
00:06:19,340 --> 00:06:23,040
 and a poor man in filthy old clothes also comes in.

155
00:06:23,040 --> 00:06:24,700
 If you show special attention

156
00:06:24,700 --> 00:06:26,100
 to the man you're wearing fine clothes,

157
00:06:26,100 --> 00:06:28,180
 say, "Here's a good seat for you,"

158
00:06:28,180 --> 00:06:30,420
 but say to the poor man, "You stand there

159
00:06:30,420 --> 00:06:32,940
 "or sit on the floor by my feet."

160
00:06:32,940 --> 00:06:35,260
 Have you not discriminated among yourselves

161
00:06:35,260 --> 00:06:38,160
 and become judges with evil thoughts?

162
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:41,860
 So one of the first things James is trying to address

163
00:06:41,860 --> 00:06:43,420
 in this part of his letter

164
00:06:43,420 --> 00:06:46,620
 is something called favoritism.

165
00:06:46,620 --> 00:06:49,280
 Now, this isn't saying that as people of faith,

166
00:06:49,280 --> 00:06:51,980
 you can't have certain preferences at all.

167
00:06:51,980 --> 00:06:53,940
 Like for example, if you like strawberry ice cream

168
00:06:53,940 --> 00:06:56,180
 instead of chocolate chip cookie dough ice cream,

169
00:06:56,180 --> 00:06:57,700
 I'd say you're a crazy person,

170
00:06:57,700 --> 00:06:59,280
 but go ahead, right, get strawberry

171
00:06:59,280 --> 00:07:01,300
 if you think that's better, right?

172
00:07:01,300 --> 00:07:03,460
 This is not what it's talking about.

173
00:07:03,460 --> 00:07:04,860
 What James is talking about

174
00:07:04,860 --> 00:07:08,320
 is a toxic, evil kind of favoritism.

175
00:07:09,220 --> 00:07:13,900
 Favoritism that is rooted in injustice and discrimination.

176
00:07:13,900 --> 00:07:16,700
 Favoritism that judges people

177
00:07:16,700 --> 00:07:20,320
 by worldly standards and values.

178
00:07:20,320 --> 00:07:24,060
 And unfortunately, the scenario James is talking about

179
00:07:24,060 --> 00:07:26,440
 happens all the time in this city in Hong Kong.

180
00:07:26,440 --> 00:07:29,180
 I'm talking about people being judged

181
00:07:29,180 --> 00:07:31,140
 by their economic status.

182
00:07:31,140 --> 00:07:34,580
 There is a disparity in the city

183
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:36,160
 between the rich and the poor,

184
00:07:36,160 --> 00:07:39,880
 and it's very clearly seen as we go about everyday life.

185
00:07:39,880 --> 00:07:44,000
 We have in Hong Kong the largest wealth inequality

186
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:45,840
 in the world.

187
00:07:45,840 --> 00:07:47,360
 Consistently, this is something

188
00:07:47,360 --> 00:07:48,500
 we shouldn't be proud about, right?

189
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:52,120
 This is one of the top three most expensive places to live.

190
00:07:52,120 --> 00:07:55,280
 Hong Kong, Singapore, Sydney, places like that.

191
00:07:55,280 --> 00:07:57,640
 In Hong Kong, it's (speaking in foreign language)

192
00:07:57,640 --> 00:08:00,280
 If you're rich, you can have it all.

193
00:08:00,280 --> 00:08:03,560
 It's often the rich that get the honor and the privileges.

194
00:08:03,560 --> 00:08:05,720
 It's often the rich get special treatment

195
00:08:05,720 --> 00:08:10,360
 and recognition, and meanwhile, the poor are overlooked.

196
00:08:10,360 --> 00:08:12,320
 The poor have to eke out a living

197
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:15,520
 in the world's most expensive city,

198
00:08:15,520 --> 00:08:19,160
 cram their families into these tiny, subdivided flats,

199
00:08:19,160 --> 00:08:21,200
 not being able to afford the many things

200
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:22,760
 that we might take for granted.

201
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:26,640
 But the truth is, and this is not a small part

202
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:31,640
 of our population, 1.39, 1.4 million people

203
00:08:31,640 --> 00:08:35,360
 in Hong Kong live below the poverty line.

204
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:38,760
 How's this for a statistic?

205
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:43,800
 Oxfam in 2024 found that the median monthly income

206
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:47,760
 for the poorest 10% of households was only $1,600,

207
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:51,480
 $1,600 per month, and this was a drop

208
00:08:51,480 --> 00:08:53,520
 from before the pandemic, okay?

209
00:08:53,520 --> 00:08:57,360
 In contrast, the wealthiest 10% of households

210
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:02,360
 have a median income of $131,000.

211
00:09:02,520 --> 00:09:05,960
 This is a rise in 10% from 2019.

212
00:09:05,960 --> 00:09:09,320
 The rich are getting richer, the poor are getting poorer,

213
00:09:09,320 --> 00:09:14,320
 a disparity of almost 90 times between these two groups.

214
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:19,520
 Now, I felt the sting of this firsthand somewhat.

215
00:09:19,520 --> 00:09:22,240
 When I was a teenager, my mom would make me

216
00:09:22,240 --> 00:09:23,920
 do all sorts of jobs, right?

217
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:26,840
 So I've worked at all kinds of, I've delivered food

218
00:09:26,840 --> 00:09:30,160
 on the street in Central, I've worked at a carnival,

219
00:09:30,160 --> 00:09:31,600
 I've worked at a doctor's office,

220
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:33,720
 there's a receptionist, all these kind of jobs.

221
00:09:33,720 --> 00:09:36,800
 Her idea was to expose me to the different ways

222
00:09:36,800 --> 00:09:39,280
 that people live from my relatively sheltered

223
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:41,040
 and comfortable life that I had,

224
00:09:41,040 --> 00:09:42,520
 so all kinds of summer jobs.

225
00:09:42,520 --> 00:09:44,800
 And one of the summers, I found myself working

226
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:47,280
 at a warehouse in Kwun Tong.

227
00:09:47,280 --> 00:09:48,960
 Now, I got the job there because my uncle

228
00:09:48,960 --> 00:09:52,280
 was the manager of the warehouse, my dad's older brother,

229
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:55,040
 right, and so, and this is the kind of place

230
00:09:55,040 --> 00:09:59,040
 where all your sort of dry goods at the supermarket

231
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:01,000
 sort of sit there before they get shipped off

232
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,840
 to the park and shops and welcomes and all that stuff.

233
00:10:02,840 --> 00:10:06,880
 So I'm talking about like toothpaste, toilet paper,

234
00:10:06,880 --> 00:10:09,360
 bleach, cleaning products, all that kind of stuff

235
00:10:09,360 --> 00:10:12,440
 is put in these warehouses, and my job was to pull them off

236
00:10:12,440 --> 00:10:14,800
 these shelves, put them into boxes ready for them

237
00:10:14,800 --> 00:10:17,680
 to be shipped to the different locations, right?

238
00:10:17,680 --> 00:10:21,460
 And it was dusty, it was dirty, it was hot.

239
00:10:21,460 --> 00:10:25,480
 My salary was 25 Hong Kong dollars an hour, okay?

240
00:10:25,480 --> 00:10:28,080
 $25 an hour, this is about the year 2000,

241
00:10:28,080 --> 00:10:29,520
 something like that.

242
00:10:29,520 --> 00:10:30,800
 Now, for me, I was just doing it

243
00:10:30,800 --> 00:10:32,840
 as some sort of an experience.

244
00:10:32,840 --> 00:10:36,200
 But I worked with two lovely old ladies

245
00:10:36,200 --> 00:10:38,800
 who would sit there with me, and I was climbing up,

246
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:41,000
 then they were packing the stuff.

247
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:43,320
 But they were doing this for a living, all right?

248
00:10:43,320 --> 00:10:48,140
 25 Hong Kong dollars to survive in Hong Kong.

249
00:10:48,140 --> 00:10:52,080
 And yet, they were some of the most generous people

250
00:10:52,080 --> 00:10:52,920
 I've ever met.

251
00:10:52,920 --> 00:10:56,160
 Every now and then, they would take me out for lunch, right?

252
00:10:56,160 --> 00:10:59,880
 This meant going down to the canteen downstairs

253
00:10:59,880 --> 00:11:03,080
 where a meal was like 25 to like $40.

254
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:06,560
 So they were spending 40, as much as I insisted,

255
00:11:06,560 --> 00:11:09,880
 I don't need this, 40% of their daily income

256
00:11:09,880 --> 00:11:13,760
 to buy me lunch, living on $25 an hour.

257
00:11:13,760 --> 00:11:17,400
 They had no idea that my uncle was their boss, right?

258
00:11:17,400 --> 00:11:20,360
 They were just doing it because they loved

259
00:11:20,360 --> 00:11:23,160
 and they cared because that was their heart.

260
00:11:23,160 --> 00:11:26,000
 Now, in the same building, there were the corporate offices

261
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 on the upper floors, right?

262
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:29,640
 This space was cool and air conditioned, right?

263
00:11:29,640 --> 00:11:31,560
 People wore suits and leather shoes,

264
00:11:31,560 --> 00:11:34,440
 making much more than $25 an hour.

265
00:11:34,440 --> 00:11:36,920
 So I remember, true story, one time I needed to go up

266
00:11:36,920 --> 00:11:39,040
 to the office floor to collect something, right?

267
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:42,720
 I was all dirty and stinky from working in the warehouse.

268
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:45,200
 I needed a drink of water, so there's a water cooler

269
00:11:45,200 --> 00:11:48,120
 right there, so I went to get a drink of water,

270
00:11:48,120 --> 00:11:50,680
 only to be stopped by a member of staff there

271
00:11:50,680 --> 00:11:53,000
 and said, "Hey, don't do that.

272
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:54,860
 "Warehouse workers aren't allowed here.

273
00:11:54,860 --> 00:11:57,800
 "If you need a drink, you need to go back downstairs.

274
00:11:57,800 --> 00:11:59,560
 "You're getting everything all dirty up here.

275
00:11:59,560 --> 00:12:00,720
 "Don't stay up here."

276
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:04,680
 The way I wanted to say, "Do you know who my uncle is?"

277
00:12:04,680 --> 00:12:08,080
 Okay, like I didn't, okay, so, right,

278
00:12:08,080 --> 00:12:09,760
 don't do that either.

279
00:12:09,760 --> 00:12:12,240
 But stuff like that happens all the time in this city, right?

280
00:12:12,240 --> 00:12:14,280
 I'm not sure, I'm sure I'm not the only one

281
00:12:14,280 --> 00:12:16,840
 who has encountered this.

282
00:12:16,840 --> 00:12:20,000
 If there ever was a city where the poor and the rich

283
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:22,040
 live right next to each other,

284
00:12:22,040 --> 00:12:24,220
 yet are treated very differently,

285
00:12:24,220 --> 00:12:25,680
 it's right here in Hong Kong.

286
00:12:25,680 --> 00:12:29,380
 Being rich gets you preferential treatment,

287
00:12:29,380 --> 00:12:32,120
 and it so happens that back then,

288
00:12:32,120 --> 00:12:34,060
 in the time of James, it was the same thing.

289
00:12:34,060 --> 00:12:36,840
 2,000 years, not much has changed.

290
00:12:36,840 --> 00:12:40,500
 Now, the question for us is,

291
00:12:40,500 --> 00:12:43,260
 would we let this happen in our church?

292
00:12:43,260 --> 00:12:45,620
 On a more personal level,

293
00:12:45,620 --> 00:12:48,380
 would you react this way yourself?

294
00:12:48,380 --> 00:12:51,900
 And James tells us in this letter

295
00:12:51,900 --> 00:12:54,280
 that if we find ourselves being inclined

296
00:12:54,280 --> 00:12:57,700
 to treat the rich with special attention,

297
00:12:57,700 --> 00:13:01,620
 but look down on the poor, this is discriminatory.

298
00:13:01,620 --> 00:13:05,020
 It's judgmental, and it's evil

299
00:13:05,020 --> 00:13:08,880
 because it goes against the very heart of God.

300
00:13:08,880 --> 00:13:13,880
 Now, of course, it's tempting to act in this way.

301
00:13:13,880 --> 00:13:15,940
 We like to cozy up to the rich and the powerful

302
00:13:15,940 --> 00:13:20,580
 because of the benefits that it might have upon us.

303
00:13:20,580 --> 00:13:22,620
 We honor them in hopes that they will give us

304
00:13:22,620 --> 00:13:25,140
 some of their money and their wealth.

305
00:13:25,140 --> 00:13:26,340
 We do it out of the way for them

306
00:13:26,340 --> 00:13:29,340
 because maybe one day, they're gonna help us back.

307
00:13:29,340 --> 00:13:31,460
 You scratch my back, I scratch yours,

308
00:13:31,460 --> 00:13:33,260
 that sort of mentality.

309
00:13:33,260 --> 00:13:36,420
 But what can a poor person offer us?

310
00:13:36,420 --> 00:13:39,540
 They're just gonna drain our resources,

311
00:13:39,540 --> 00:13:42,080
 drain our time, there is no benefit

312
00:13:42,080 --> 00:13:44,560
 when we pay special attention to them.

313
00:13:44,560 --> 00:13:48,820
 Now, listen, church, this might be the way the world works,

314
00:13:48,820 --> 00:13:53,820
 but it is ungodly and incompatible with our faith

315
00:13:53,820 --> 00:13:56,140
 as Christians for us to act this way.

316
00:13:56,140 --> 00:14:02,340
 It's evil because it goes against God's heart.

317
00:14:02,340 --> 00:14:03,500
 And as we look through scripture,

318
00:14:03,500 --> 00:14:06,180
 God's heart has always been to side himself

319
00:14:06,180 --> 00:14:08,580
 with the poor and the needy.

320
00:14:08,580 --> 00:14:11,380
 Think about the way Jesus entered into this world.

321
00:14:11,380 --> 00:14:15,540
 He didn't come in might, in pomp, in splendor.

322
00:14:15,540 --> 00:14:20,500
 He could have, but instead he came humbly, meek,

323
00:14:20,500 --> 00:14:23,900
 with nothing, nothing that we look upon

324
00:14:23,900 --> 00:14:26,640
 that we could desire, physically speaking.

325
00:14:26,640 --> 00:14:30,500
 He chose to identify with the poor

326
00:14:30,500 --> 00:14:32,200
 as he came into this world.

327
00:14:32,200 --> 00:14:36,060
 2 Corinthians 2:9 tells us that though Jesus was rich,

328
00:14:36,060 --> 00:14:39,360
 yet for your sake, he became poor.

329
00:14:39,360 --> 00:14:43,180
 And so how God calls us as a people of faith

330
00:14:43,180 --> 00:14:46,180
 to work as opposites of how the world works.

331
00:14:46,180 --> 00:14:48,300
 He tells us that it is the poor

332
00:14:48,300 --> 00:14:50,660
 that we should pay attention to.

333
00:14:50,660 --> 00:14:53,680
 It is the poor that we should open our hands wide to,

334
00:14:53,680 --> 00:14:55,800
 Deuteronomy 15, 11.

335
00:14:55,800 --> 00:14:57,600
 It is the poor that we should be inviting

336
00:14:57,600 --> 00:14:59,620
 to our dinners and our banquets.

337
00:14:59,620 --> 00:15:00,740
 That's in the book of Luke.

338
00:15:00,740 --> 00:15:02,680
 It is the poor that the weak,

339
00:15:02,680 --> 00:15:04,340
 that we must work hard to help.

340
00:15:04,340 --> 00:15:06,900
 Or the poor and the weak that we must work hard to help,

341
00:15:06,900 --> 00:15:08,400
 Acts 20.

342
00:15:08,400 --> 00:15:12,260
 It is the poor that we are called to sell everything

343
00:15:12,260 --> 00:15:14,300
 and give it to them, Matthew 19.

344
00:15:14,300 --> 00:15:18,100
 And this beautifully is summarized

345
00:15:18,100 --> 00:15:22,300
 in what James calls in his letter, the royal law.

346
00:15:22,300 --> 00:15:23,980
 It is the royal law because he got this

347
00:15:23,980 --> 00:15:28,240
 from his brother, Jesus himself, who is the king of kings.

348
00:15:28,240 --> 00:15:32,260
 It's what Jesus called as part of the greatest commandment.

349
00:15:32,260 --> 00:15:36,260
 You are to love your neighbor as yourself.

350
00:15:36,260 --> 00:15:39,700
 And our neighbor's church are the needy,

351
00:15:39,700 --> 00:15:42,300
 the widows, the orphans, the poor.

352
00:15:42,300 --> 00:15:47,420
 A genuine faith in Jesus will never show favoritism

353
00:15:47,420 --> 00:15:51,180
 to the rich in expense of the poor.

354
00:15:51,180 --> 00:15:54,300
 A genuine faith in Jesus will always take action

355
00:15:54,300 --> 00:15:57,940
 and be the hands and feet that he has called us to be.

356
00:15:57,940 --> 00:16:01,260
 And by the way, favoritism and discrimination

357
00:16:01,260 --> 00:16:03,220
 isn't just about rich and poor.

358
00:16:03,220 --> 00:16:05,700
 Any form of discrimination and favoritism

359
00:16:05,700 --> 00:16:10,540
 that dishonors people is a dishonor and an insult to God

360
00:16:10,540 --> 00:16:13,520
 because we have been made in his image.

361
00:16:13,520 --> 00:16:19,100
 But James is using the rich and the poor here as an example.

362
00:16:19,100 --> 00:16:21,300
 And to really drive this point home,

363
00:16:21,300 --> 00:16:23,900
 he goes on to deliver one of the hardest hitting,

364
00:16:23,900 --> 00:16:27,780
 maybe one of the most controversial and challenging passages

365
00:16:27,780 --> 00:16:29,060
 in the whole of scripture.

366
00:16:29,060 --> 00:16:30,960
 He tells us this.

367
00:16:30,960 --> 00:16:34,540
 What good is it, my brothers and sisters,

368
00:16:34,540 --> 00:16:37,740
 if someone claims to have faith but has no deeds?

369
00:16:37,740 --> 00:16:39,480
 Can such faith save them?

370
00:16:39,480 --> 00:16:43,140
 Suppose a brother or sister is without clothes

371
00:16:43,140 --> 00:16:44,200
 and daily food.

372
00:16:44,200 --> 00:16:45,540
 If one of you says to them,

373
00:16:45,540 --> 00:16:47,900
 "Go in peace, keep warm and well fed,"

374
00:16:47,900 --> 00:16:50,340
 but does nothing about their physical needs,

375
00:16:50,340 --> 00:16:52,020
 what good is it?

376
00:16:52,020 --> 00:16:55,080
 In the same way, faith by itself,

377
00:16:55,080 --> 00:16:59,420
 if it's not accompanied by action, is dead.

378
00:16:59,420 --> 00:17:02,520
 Now I say this is controversial

379
00:17:02,520 --> 00:17:06,180
 because it seems to contradict what we love about our faith.

380
00:17:06,180 --> 00:17:11,180
 Our faith tells us that Jesus loves us no matter what

381
00:17:11,180 --> 00:17:14,420
 and that there's nothing more that we can do

382
00:17:14,420 --> 00:17:16,860
 to make him love us.

383
00:17:16,860 --> 00:17:19,500
 We say that salvation is a free gift, right?

384
00:17:19,500 --> 00:17:21,620
 It's salvation, grace and forgiveness.

385
00:17:21,620 --> 00:17:23,360
 It's a free gift of God.

386
00:17:23,360 --> 00:17:26,540
 There is nothing we can do to earn that kind of love

387
00:17:26,540 --> 00:17:28,120
 that God has for us.

388
00:17:28,120 --> 00:17:32,500
 And I would say yes and amen to these statements.

389
00:17:32,500 --> 00:17:33,820
 But it seems as though right now,

390
00:17:33,820 --> 00:17:35,440
 James is saying that there are certain things,

391
00:17:35,440 --> 00:17:38,280
 actually, you do have to do for our faith.

392
00:17:38,280 --> 00:17:41,500
 That faith alone is not enough.

393
00:17:41,500 --> 00:17:46,040
 And I would say the answer to that question is also yes.

394
00:17:46,040 --> 00:17:48,460
 Because remember the point we're trying to answer,

395
00:17:48,460 --> 00:17:50,240
 with the point we made at the beginning,

396
00:17:50,240 --> 00:17:52,860
 the point Philip pointed us towards last week.

397
00:17:52,860 --> 00:17:56,380
 We are trying to determine whether our faith is real.

398
00:17:56,380 --> 00:18:00,160
 We are trying to figure out what this pure religion is.

399
00:18:00,160 --> 00:18:05,160
 And pure religion, real faith has to be backed up by action.

400
00:18:05,160 --> 00:18:07,420
 Now don't get me wrong, okay?

401
00:18:07,420 --> 00:18:10,740
 I'm not saying that your actions are going to save you.

402
00:18:10,740 --> 00:18:13,300
 That's not the point, that's bad theology.

403
00:18:13,300 --> 00:18:16,580
 This isn't what James is trying to say either.

404
00:18:16,580 --> 00:18:18,060
 But what we're trying to say

405
00:18:18,060 --> 00:18:20,660
 is that those who truly follow Jesus

406
00:18:20,660 --> 00:18:24,140
 will always be able to show you in some way

407
00:18:24,140 --> 00:18:25,980
 that the faith is real.

408
00:18:25,980 --> 00:18:29,720
 Genuine faith has real deeds behind it.

409
00:18:30,420 --> 00:18:32,740
 Right, this is how, when I was doing some research,

410
00:18:32,740 --> 00:18:34,820
 this is how one of the commentaries put it.

411
00:18:34,820 --> 00:18:38,540
 James is not arguing that works must be added to faith.

412
00:18:38,540 --> 00:18:41,940
 His point, rather, is that genuine biblical faith

413
00:18:41,940 --> 00:18:46,580
 will inevitably be characterized by works.

414
00:18:46,580 --> 00:18:49,220
 These are hard-hitting questions,

415
00:18:49,220 --> 00:18:50,900
 but we need to get to the bottom of it

416
00:18:50,900 --> 00:18:55,760
 because our entire relationship with Jesus is on the line.

417
00:18:55,760 --> 00:18:58,140
 James asks us, what good is it, my brothers,

418
00:18:58,140 --> 00:19:00,940
 if someone claims to have faith but has no deeds?

419
00:19:00,940 --> 00:19:03,460
 Can such faith save them?

420
00:19:03,460 --> 00:19:05,040
 Let's answer these questions.

421
00:19:05,040 --> 00:19:07,760
 Notice first that James says claims.

422
00:19:07,760 --> 00:19:12,020
 Now look, just because we claim something,

423
00:19:12,020 --> 00:19:14,140
 it doesn't always mean it's true.

424
00:19:14,140 --> 00:19:15,940
 People make all sorts of wild claims,

425
00:19:15,940 --> 00:19:18,860
 but if we believed everything that everyone said,

426
00:19:18,860 --> 00:19:20,320
 we would be fools.

427
00:19:20,320 --> 00:19:22,500
 I could tell you that LeBron James and I,

428
00:19:22,500 --> 00:19:24,300
 we have the same basketball skills, okay?

429
00:19:24,300 --> 00:19:26,660
 What he can do on the court, I can do too.

430
00:19:26,660 --> 00:19:28,260
 I can do a slam dunk and shoot threes.

431
00:19:28,260 --> 00:19:30,780
 I can do all that kind of stuff, right?

432
00:19:30,780 --> 00:19:32,400
 You would rightly say, okay, prove it, right?

433
00:19:32,400 --> 00:19:35,860
 There's a court right down there next to the MTR station.

434
00:19:35,860 --> 00:19:38,740
 Bring a basketball, show me your skills.

435
00:19:38,740 --> 00:19:41,340
 And it's the same thing when it comes to our faith.

436
00:19:41,340 --> 00:19:44,020
 If someone claims to have a faith in Jesus,

437
00:19:44,020 --> 00:19:47,720
 they should be able to show you evidence of their faith.

438
00:19:47,720 --> 00:19:48,980
 Otherwise, how will we know

439
00:19:48,980 --> 00:19:51,140
 that what they're saying is true?

440
00:19:51,140 --> 00:19:54,620
 We can't unless we see their faith in action.

441
00:19:55,820 --> 00:19:59,340
 And the second part of that question is even a bit scarier.

442
00:19:59,340 --> 00:20:03,140
 Like I said, these things have eternal consequences.

443
00:20:03,140 --> 00:20:08,060
 One of the main motivations that people have

444
00:20:08,060 --> 00:20:11,100
 in the journey of faith and becoming a Christian

445
00:20:11,100 --> 00:20:14,900
 is because they want some sort of assurance of salvation.

446
00:20:14,900 --> 00:20:18,020
 They want to know that after they die,

447
00:20:18,020 --> 00:20:20,920
 they're not gonna end up in some horrible place called hell,

448
00:20:20,920 --> 00:20:23,500
 but rather live out all of eternity in heaven

449
00:20:23,500 --> 00:20:25,000
 where there's joy and bliss

450
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:28,140
 and all the nice, wonderful things you can think of.

451
00:20:28,140 --> 00:20:32,780
 Now, going to heaven, being in the kingdom of God

452
00:20:32,780 --> 00:20:34,860
 for all eternity after we die,

453
00:20:34,860 --> 00:20:38,420
 salvation, eternal life is a promise

454
00:20:38,420 --> 00:20:41,060
 and a reward from Jesus.

455
00:20:41,060 --> 00:20:45,860
 But only for those who have a real and genuine faith

456
00:20:45,860 --> 00:20:50,660
 that demonstrates real acts of service and love

457
00:20:50,660 --> 00:20:52,060
 to those around us.

458
00:20:52,900 --> 00:20:54,900
 So the answer to the question is no.

459
00:20:54,900 --> 00:20:58,680
 A faith that does not live itself out with deeds

460
00:20:58,680 --> 00:21:03,020
 is not the kind of faith that leads to salvation.

461
00:21:03,020 --> 00:21:07,360
 James makes it even clearer for us.

462
00:21:07,360 --> 00:21:09,200
 He gives another scenario for us to imagine.

463
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:12,880
 He says, suppose a brother or sister

464
00:21:12,880 --> 00:21:15,000
 is without clothes or daily food.

465
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:17,800
 If one of you says to them, go in peace,

466
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:19,320
 keep warm and well-fed,

467
00:21:19,340 --> 00:21:23,140
 but does nothing about their physical needs,

468
00:21:23,140 --> 00:21:25,120
 what good is it?

469
00:21:25,120 --> 00:21:30,060
 It's not a complicated question.

470
00:21:30,060 --> 00:21:32,200
 The answer is simple.

471
00:21:32,200 --> 00:21:35,100
 The Cantonese translation for this type of situation

472
00:21:35,100 --> 00:21:37,680
 is [speaks in foreign language]

473
00:21:37,680 --> 00:21:40,140
 It's kind of like an insult we use in Cantonese.

474
00:21:40,140 --> 00:21:43,260
 If you see someone in need but you don't help them,

475
00:21:43,260 --> 00:21:47,900
 it's like a pitiful, shameful thing to do.

476
00:21:47,900 --> 00:21:49,400
 So what good is it, asks James.

477
00:21:49,400 --> 00:21:51,480
 The answer is it's no good.

478
00:21:51,480 --> 00:21:54,120
 Faith that is not accompanied by action

479
00:21:54,120 --> 00:21:56,960
 is a dead kind of faith.

480
00:21:56,960 --> 00:22:00,360
 It's no good just to give people your words and well wishes

481
00:22:00,360 --> 00:22:03,740
 when the needs that they have are right in front of you.

482
00:22:03,740 --> 00:22:06,840
 It's interesting because this kind of behavior

483
00:22:06,840 --> 00:22:07,840
 sort of makes sense.

484
00:22:07,840 --> 00:22:10,360
 If you follow on from what James was talking about before,

485
00:22:10,360 --> 00:22:12,800
 well, if we're only showing favoritism to the rich

486
00:22:12,800 --> 00:22:14,320
 and the powerful and the wealthy,

487
00:22:14,320 --> 00:22:16,120
 well, they don't really need anything,

488
00:22:16,120 --> 00:22:18,940
 and so there's nothing really we can do for them,

489
00:22:18,940 --> 00:22:21,660
 and so when the needs of the poor are presented to us,

490
00:22:21,660 --> 00:22:23,700
 we too are inclined to do nothing

491
00:22:23,700 --> 00:22:24,860
 'cause it doesn't benefit us.

492
00:22:24,860 --> 00:22:27,860
 There's nothing in it for us.

493
00:22:27,860 --> 00:22:30,580
 But at the same time, of course, now, we're not monsters,

494
00:22:30,580 --> 00:22:33,140
 and so let's give them a prayer.

495
00:22:33,140 --> 00:22:34,460
 We don't wanna totally ignore them.

496
00:22:34,460 --> 00:22:36,500
 Let's scratch that itch on our conscience

497
00:22:36,500 --> 00:22:39,540
 and give them our well wishes and send them on their way.

498
00:22:39,540 --> 00:22:41,220
 At least we did something, right?

499
00:22:43,760 --> 00:22:46,280
 I've been asking myself, and I ask you, church,

500
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:48,340
 is that what Jesus would do?

501
00:22:48,340 --> 00:22:53,560
 Does that reflect God's heart for his children?

502
00:22:53,560 --> 00:22:58,140
 And in preparing the message series in James

503
00:22:58,140 --> 00:22:59,740
 and in working with our team,

504
00:22:59,740 --> 00:23:02,540
 I went through and I'm currently going through

505
00:23:02,540 --> 00:23:05,820
 a lot of wrestling when it comes to this message

506
00:23:05,820 --> 00:23:08,060
 because if I'm honest, quite often,

507
00:23:08,060 --> 00:23:10,820
 when it comes to a situation like this,

508
00:23:10,820 --> 00:23:13,500
 I feel like my reaction doesn't always reflect

509
00:23:13,500 --> 00:23:14,740
 the faith that I claim.

510
00:23:14,740 --> 00:23:17,680
 When there's physical needs in front of me

511
00:23:17,680 --> 00:23:22,600
 that are to be met, sometimes I panic, I shrink back,

512
00:23:22,600 --> 00:23:24,680
 I don't want to do anything about it.

513
00:23:24,680 --> 00:23:25,640
 And I make excuses.

514
00:23:25,640 --> 00:23:28,440
 Oh, well, you know, if I help them now,

515
00:23:28,440 --> 00:23:30,180
 I'm gonna be stuck helping them forever.

516
00:23:30,180 --> 00:23:32,780
 I don't have the time and the resources for that.

